At the age of eleven, he learned his first guitar.
At the age of 15, the teenager began to play professional guitar and five years later got the chance to be on stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
Shortly thereafter, he was hired by the Bluesbreakers as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967, along with fellow Bluesbreakers Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross", composed by Green, gave the group their first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green could not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on the life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that's happened to me in my life is drugs - the best thing was to land a number one hit".
Towards the end of the decade, Green surprisingly achieved a cult success with an album inspired by religious themes in 1979.
Meanwhile Fleetwood Mac floated without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite several minor solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until 1996, when he rejoined a group of fellow musicians.
The British "Daily Telegraph" then spoke of a rock star who had returned to Earth.
Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band broke up in 2004.
For music experts he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
